If you need to install the worldfootballR package (which you probably do), dont forget to install it.

install.packages("worldfootballR")

Now Im going to load the packages I need for this session.

library(tidyverse)
library(worldfootballR)

We can use the fb_match_results() function from worldfootballR to get match results from fbref.com. Thats the data were going to use for this exercise.

FYI, dont worry about this if you find it confusing, but if youre looking at the .Rmd file, youll see that Ive added the option cache=TRUE to the code chunk. This caches the result of the chunk and saves it locally. I did this so I dont re-download the data every single time from the website. RStudio will stash this information in the project folder and use it as needed. If it cant find the information in the cache, or if I modify the chunk at all, it will download it again.

# get premier league match results for three seasons
d <- fb_match_results(
  country = "ENG",               # England
  gender = "M",                  # men's football ("soccer")
  season_end_year = 2020:2022,   # asking for three seasons: 19-20, 20-21, and 21-22
  tier = "1st"                   # 1st division (Premier League)
)

Now that we have created the data, we can glimpse() it to get a sense of what kind of information it contains.

The dataset, d, has 1140 matches from three seasons and several variables associated with each match.

For this exercise, we are going to use xG or expected goals. Here is a video explaining how xG works and why its so important to soccer analytics.

In ModernDive chapter 2, the authors talk about the 5NG or five named graphs. I am going to demonstrate each one here using the data we have downloaded.

Scatterplot

Lets plot home xG against away xG. We will use geom_jitter() instead of geom_point() to avoid overplotting. We can also add transparency to our points using alpha. Finally, I am going to add theme_minimal() to all my graphs because I think it looks better.

## simplest version
ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Home_xG,
           y = Away_xG)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .2) +
  theme_minimal()

Line Graph

Line graphs are usually used when you have a running variable (like a date or time) along the x-axis and a quantitative variable on the y-axis. The easiest way to do this is to plot something for just a single team (so there arent multiple events on the same day.)

Our first step will be to make a subset of the data thats just one teams home matches. We will use Liverpool. Dont worry too much about how to do this because you havent learned it yet.

lfc <- d |> 
  filter(Home == "Liverpool")

This code has made a new data frame, lfc, which is just Liverpools home matches across the three seasons. Again, dont worry too much about how I did this.

Lets plot Liverpools home xG against time and see if we see any patterns.

ggplot(lfc,
       aes(x = Date,
           y = Home_xG)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal()

This is very noisy! Its hard to tell visually if there are any patterns. One way to deal with this is to add a smoother a line that smooths out the trend. We can use geom_smooth() for this, which adds a new line based on locally-weighted least squares (dont worry about this!).

ggplot(lfc,
       aes(x = Date,
           y = Home_xG)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth() +            # this is the new bit
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

By default, the smooth line is blue, a solid line, and has a gray ribbon around it that reflects statistical uncertainty. We can change all those if we want.

ggplot(lfc,
       aes(x = Date,
           y = Home_xG)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE,              # no "standard error" (uncertainty ribbon)
              color = "red",           # color of line
              linetype = "dashed") +   # style of line
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

It looks like Liverpool had a bit of a dip in offensive production toward the end of the 2020-21 season but recovered strongly the next season.

Histogram

Unlike the two graphs above, this one just represents one quantitative variable. Lets go back to the full dataset, d, and look at the distribution of home xG.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Home_xG)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_minimal()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

This is a histogram but its pretty ugly to be honest. By default, geom_histogram() just makes 30 equally-spaced bins and that may or may not make sense. We can do better.

The main things we can control are where the first bin starts, how wide the bins are, and the visual demarcation between the bars.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Home_xG)) +
  geom_histogram(boundary = 0,        # start the first bin at 0
                 binwidth = .2,       # make the bins .2 (xG) units wide  
                 color = "white") +   # make the bin borders white
  theme_minimal()

This looks better. We can improve this even more by tweaking the x-axis.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Home_xG)) +
  geom_histogram(boundary = 0,        
                 binwidth = .2,         
                 color = "white") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 0,    # start labeling at 0
                                  to = 6,      # stop at 6
                                  by = .5),    # put a break every .5
                     minor_breaks = NULL) +    # only lines we asked for
  theme_minimal()

This makes the x-axis a bit easier to interpret. The most common home xG values are around 1.

Bar graph

There are two good uses for bar graphs. The first one (not discussed in ModernDive) is when you have some data you would use for a histogram but you dont have to chop it up into bins because it already has low resolution. A good example of this is actual goals scored per game. It already comes in integers (0, 1, 2, etc.) so we dont need to bin it like we do with a histogram.

Lets look at actual home goals (instead of expected goals). We use geom_bar() here instead of geom_histogram().

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = HomeGoals)) +
  geom_bar() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:9,
                     minor_breaks = NULL) +
  labs(title = "Home Goals Scored, EPL 2019-2022",  # title
       x = "# of Goals",                            # x title
       y = "# of Games") +                          # y title
  theme_minimal()

The second use (covered in ModernDive) is when you have a non-quantitative variable you want to represent. Lets look at how many games are played on each day of the week.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Day)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_minimal()

The most obvious thing wrong with this is that the x-axis ordering makes zero sense! We can order the x-axis two reasonable ways: in time order (since days of the week do have an order) or in frequency order (most to least common). Were not ready for the second one yet but lets do the first one.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = factor(
         Day,
         levels = c("Mon",
                    "Tue",
                    "Wed",
                    "Thu",
                    "Fri",
                    "Sat",
                    "Sun")
       ))) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_minimal()

This code looks a lot more complicated (and messy, tbh) but all weve done is wrap the Day variable in factor() and add levels so we get the order we want. I dont expect you to know how to do this without looking my code (or searching).

Even though it gets the x-axis order right, it makes the x-axis title super ugly as a side effect. We can change it (and add other titles while were at it).

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = factor(
         Day,
         levels = c("Mon",
                    "Tue",
                    "Wed",
                    "Thu",
                    "Fri",
                    "Sat",
                    "Sun")
       ))) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Day of the Week",
       y = "# of Matches",
       title = "Premier League Matches by Day of the Week, 2019-2022") +
  theme_minimal()

All of the versions of the bar graph make it clear that Saturday is the most common day for English Premier League matches.

Boxplot

The last graph well cover is the box plot. This is usually most useful when you have a continuous variable that you want to compare across levels of a categorical (discrete) variable.

Lets look at an example. Most (all?) of the 2020-2021 season was played without any fans in the stadiums. Was the home xG for this season worse than for the surrounding seasons?

Lets try looking at this question with a boxplot. Warning: this isnt going to work well the first time we try it!

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Season_End_Year,
           y = Home_xG)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Continuous x aesthetic -- did you forget aes(group=...)?

The x-axis looks weird here because R doesnt know that we want separate box plots per season. This is because Season_End_Year isnt a factor or a character. Lets look:

class(d$Season_End_Year)
## [1] "integer"

If we want side-by-side plots of xG by season, we need to make Season_End_Year a factor variable. We can just wrap it in factor(), as you can see.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = factor(Season_End_Year),
           y = Home_xG)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal()

This looks better. We could clean it up a bit. But we can see that the median (the thick black line in the middle of the box) is a little lower in 2021 (which is the 2020-21 season). So maybe no fans really did make a difference?

One final thing: sometimes its better to compare boxplots the other way. We can use coord_flip() to swap the x and y axes.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = factor(Season_End_Year),
           y = Home_xG)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal()
